    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1925171465" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1925171465" />
    <a title="leynes" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45198798-leynes"><img alt="leynes" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593512704p2/45198798.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1925171465?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="leynes" class="user" itemprop="url" name="leynes" href="/user/show/45198798-leynes">leynes</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007252251" href="/book/show/821431.The_Children_of_H_rin">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1925171465" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10296607817297084051">Tolkien back at it again with the epic tales that blow my mind and make me cry. I totally didn&apos;t expect the latter to happen but then the last two (!) pages took me completely by surprise and actually broke my heart. All the feeels!<br/><br/>I will scream it from the rooftops: Tolkien is a force to be reckoned with. This man is the perfect combination of a genius, a nerd, a fangirl and an academic. All of his narratives combine elements which I highly cherish in a good (fantasy) story: a complex and authe</span>
  <span id="freeText10296607817297084051" style="display:none">Tolkien back at it again with the epic tales that blow my mind and make me cry. I totally didn't expect the latter to happen but then the last two (!) pages took me completely by surprise and actually broke my heart. All the feeels!<br /><br />I will scream it from the rooftops: Tolkien is a force to be reckoned with. This man is the perfect combination of a genius, a nerd, a fangirl and an academic. All of his narratives combine elements which I highly cherish in a good (fantasy) story: a complex and authentic setting, an epic plot that culminates in an even more epic climax, a satisfying ending, and readable writing. <br /><br />Tolkien is not necessarily my favorite author, because I struggle with the density of some of his work (especially <i>The Lord of the Rings</i>), but I absolutely adore his earlier writings and everything not concerning the Third Age. Don't get me wrong, I still highly enjoyed <i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, I just think that his mythological and shorter tales are much more approachable, and they sure pack an emotional punch.<blockquote>
  <b>But a man must speak as he sees, nor hide the truth that he believes.</b>
</blockquote><i>The Children of Húrin</i> is based on the Finnish legend of <i>Kullervo</i>. It is the tragic tale of Túrin Turambar and his sister Niënor Níniel. The themes explored include evil, free will and predestination. Despite Túrin's character being shaped by Morgoth's curse, he is still partly responsible for his actions, and displays traits like arrogance, pride and a desire for honour, that eventually cause the doom of his allies and family. <br /><br />Going into this I already knew what the 'plot twists' would be (due to my reading of <i>The Silmarillion</i> in which a shorter version of this tale is featured), nonetheless it still hit me quite hard. I didn't feel that connected to Túrin himself, but the rest of his family, especially his younger sister and his mother, really grew close to me, and to read of their suffering really got to me. <br /><br />There's lots to say in regards of lack of female characters as a whole and lack of female agency in <i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, however I was pleasantly surprised with how the female characters in <i>The Children of Húrin</i> were written. Especially Morwen and Niënor were portrayed as much more courageous and independant than most of the male characters, and I loved that they basically didn't give a shit about permissions, and listened to their own values and instincts. Also, characters got called out for mistreating women... like YAAAS (e.g. when Túrin chased Saeros from Doriath, or when Túrin openly rebuked rape and kept the outlaws from committing it). <br /><br />There are still one too many instances were women are seen as weepy and dying of grief, but, to be fair, the male characters also have their fair share of sorrows and display a lot of 'vulnerable' emotions, and listen to 'love rather than wisdom'. I especially liked the bit towards the end where Túrin, after being praised for his valor, said: 'I care not, <b>for my heart is also slain.</b>'<br /><br />In general, the tale is quite rich in theme and so, for example, Mîm's exchange with Andróg is very interesting from an analytical point of view:<blockquote>'Where is this house of yours?' said Andróg. 'It must be good indeed to share it with a Dwarf. For Andróg doesn't like Dwarves. His people brought few good tales of that race out of the East.'<br /><b>'They left worse tales of themselves behind,'</b> said Mîm.</blockquote>This exchange is not only coined by racism and racial prejudices, but also shows the blissfully ignorant nature of the aggressor (Andróg of the race of Men) and the nature of colonialism. <br /><br />All there's left to say is that I am impressed with how easily this story flowed and how thorough it was. I really appreciate Christopher Tolkien's care for detail when it comes to editing his father's vast unfinished manuscripts. <br /><br />Totally random but Ulmo is my favorite Vala, and whenever he is mentioned my heart just sings. He seems to be the only one who even remotely cared for the Second Children of Ilúvatar. Also, Tolkien kept spoiling me with his chapter titles (lmao dudeee why do you name your chapter <i>The Death of [insert character names here]</i>) but that's okay. ;) I can't wait to dive deeper into his mythology!</span>
  <a data-text-id="10296607817297084051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


